If you want to think using a computer - if you ever have occasion to use the keyboard to enter text. //Especially// if you produce any sort of substantial written output, including computer code - you MUST learn to touchtype.

Take it from me - I feel your pain - I don't speak from a position of great authority - I, like you, was a long hold out in the two-fingered valley.

I could go real fast with 2 fingers, sometimes 3 or 4 might get involved if I was feeling fancy.

I timed myself at 30 words a minute - but the problem was that my head was jusat going backwards and forwards between the keyboard and the screen all the time - now that I've learned how to touchtype - and I'm only //just// at the point where I can say that honestly without feeling like a fraud, 

What you need to do is get past the pain threshold.

When you're learning something new, you have to go past the pain threshold - all, or most, of your initial practise will be painfully unsatisfying - if you're unlucky, though by no means atypical, you will experience little of the actual benefit that you're hoping to derive from the experience - you will be left at 

